                              <td valign="top" style="font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color:#333333; font-size:12px; text-align:justify;">                                Or even Spain. Then again, maybe the new “crisis” will have something to do with China, always a fertile fi eld of potential disturbances its dollar holdings, its property bubble and infl ation, its banks and thus always a reliable source of apocalyptic possibilities. Here at home, credit card use has turned up again, with as many as a third of Americans using them to buy necessities they can’t otherwise aff ord, according to Pricewaterhouse Coopers. The tapped-out American consumer is a narrative staple in fi nancial journalism. And in a pinch, there’s always the unemployment situation. That can be used to “explain” any market decline, even one of forty-five minutes’ duration. This is not just another plea that you not let yourself get frightened out of your long-term portfolio by current events. It’s both narrower and more pointed than that. It’s the strong suggestion that when, as now, the market is studiously ignoring the apocalypse du jour, even as media hysteria escalates, it is usually the market which turns out to be right in the long run.<em> © 2011 Nick Murray. All rights reserved. Reprinted by permission.</em></td>
